ce:section.ce:para:
Initial concentrations of 20 mg L−1 to 200 mg L−1 Hg2+ were used with the FHAP. Adsorption isotherms are the equilibrium relation to adsorbed concentrations (Hg2+). In the current work, the Langmuir and Freundlich models were applied to define the equilibrium data, where the Langmuir model is based on the theory that uptake occurs on a homogenous surface by monolayer sorption with no interaction between adsorbed molecules while the Freundlich model offers a monolayer sorption with heterogeneous energetic distribution of active sites and with interaction between adsorbed molecules [41–44]. The adsorption isotherm parameters are summarized in Table 1
                        . The analysis of the experimental data by Langmuir model shows an acceptable R2 value of 0.9967. These data are in favor of a mechanism involving monolayer adsorption of the analyte ions to the FHAP surface. FHAP has the maximum amount of adsorption (qmax) of Hg2+ at 227.27 mg g−1 which shows a greater Hg2+ affinity of FHAP than conventional adsorbents (see Table 2
                        ). Usual adsorbents applied in removing Hg2+ such as the commercially available activated carbon provide a qmax value of 12 mg g−1, which is less than the value for FHAP. The qmax of magnetic polypyrrole-graphene oxide composite is higher than FHAP, but the cost of it is higher and fabrication of this material is also highly complicated. Taking both capacity and cost into account, the FHAP is the best choice. The equilibrium time of this work was determined to be 20 min, which is shorter than the reported values over other adsorbents. In summary, this material can be utilized as a good adsorbent for waste-water treatment. However, to substantiate the presence of mercury on the FHAP matrix, it was corroborated with the EDS analysis (Fig. 10
                        ) which distinctly shows the presence of mercury after adsorption of the Hg2+ solution (Fig. 10(b)).
